04755nam a22006495i 9780674276994DE-B159720220629043637.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220629t20221995mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742769947 a10.4159/97806742769942doi  a(DE-B1597)626021  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aLAW0000002bisacsh1 aPost, Robert C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aConstitutional Domains :bDemocracy, Community, Management /cRobert C. Post. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (480 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Social Domains of Constitutional Law -- tI Community and Human Dignity -- t1 Theories of Constitutional Interpretation -- t2 The Social Foundations of Privacy: Community and Self in the Common Law Tort -- t3 Cultural Heterogeneity and Law: Pornography, Blasphemy, and the First Amendment -- tII Democracy and Human Freedom -- t4 The Constitutional Concept of Public Discourse: Outrageous Opinion, Democratic Deliberation, and Hustler Magazine v. Falwell -- t5 Between Democracy and Community: The Legal Constitution of Social Form -- tIII Management and Instrumental Reason -- t6 Between Governance and Management: The History and Theory of the Public Forum -- t7 Meiklejohn’s Mistake: Individual Autonomy and the Reform of Public Discourse -- tReprise: The Racist Speech Problem -- tNotes -- tSources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn a series of remarkable forays, Robert Post develops an original account of how law functions in a democratic society. His work offers a radically new perspective on some of the most pressing constitutional issues of our day, such as the regulation of racist speech, pornography, and privacy. Drawing on work in sociology, philosophy, and political theory, Post demonstrates that the law establishes distinct and competing forms of social order: democracy, in which the law embodies the possibilities of collective self-determination; community, in which the law articulates and enforces a common social identity; and management, in which the law creates the conditions for accomplishing specific goals. Debates over the boundaries between these distinct domains, Post argues, are central to some of the most intractable problems of modern constitutional law. Here we see, for instance, how the controversy over the regulation of racist speech negotiates the boundary between communitarian and democratic forms of social ordering. We see how public forum doctrine, a crucial but notoriously mysterious component of First Amendment jurisprudence, arbitrates distinctions between the social domains of democracy and management. Taking up specific court cases, such as that against Hustler magazine and that allowing prayers before state legislatures, Post shows us what is actually at stake in these constitutional struggles. A highly complex and sophisticated account of the operation of constitutional law in modern society, Constitutional Domains is essential reading for lawyers, social theorists, and makers of public policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067427699440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674276994423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674276994/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL